      <h1 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem);font-weight:400;color:#f0ece4;line-height:1.12;letter-spacing:-0.02em;margin-bottom:1.5rem;">
        Letters of Administration and Selling a Queensland Property Without a Will
      </h1>
      <p style="font-size:1rem;color:rgba(240,236,228,0.6);line-height:1.8;max-width:54ch;">
        When someone dies intestate, their property is frozen until a court authorises an administrator to act. Here is how the process works and what families selling under these circumstances need to know.
      </p>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Body -->
  <div style="padding:3rem 0 7rem;">
    <div class="max-w-[780px] mx-auto px-8" style="font-size:0.97rem;color:var(--color-text-secondary);line-height:1.9;display:flex;flex-direction:column;gap:1.75rem;">

      <p>When a property owner dies without a valid will, the people closest to them face a situation that combines grief with administrative and legal complexity. The property is part of the estate and cannot simply be sold because family members agree it should be. Before anyone can deal with real property on behalf of the deceased, the Supreme Court of Queensland must authorise someone to act as administrator. That authorisation comes in the form of letters of administration, and understanding what they are, who can apply, and what the timeline looks like is essential for any family managing a property sale in these circumstances.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Dying without a will: the intestacy rules apply</h2>
      <p>When a person dies intestate (without a valid will), Queensland's Succession Act 1981 determines how their estate is distributed. The rules create a priority order among beneficiaries: a spouse or de facto partner comes first, followed by children, then other next of kin in a defined sequence. The estate does not automatically pass to the family. Distribution can only happen after an administrator has been appointed and has formally dealt with the assets. Until that point, the property is legally frozen.</p>

      <p>Probate, which many families are familiar with as the process for dealing with a deceased estate, applies when the deceased left a valid will. The executor named in the will applies for a grant of probate, which confirms their authority to administer the estate. Letters of administration serve the same function for intestate estates: they are the court's confirmation that a specific person has authority to act. The documents are different, the application process differs in some respects, but the legal effect is the same.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Who can apply to be administrator</h2>
      <p>The court follows a priority order when deciding who should be appointed administrator, which broadly mirrors the succession priority. A surviving spouse or de facto partner has the first right to apply. If there is no surviving spouse, children of the deceased can apply. Other next of kin follow in order. If no family member is willing or able to act, the Public Trustee of Queensland can be appointed. Where two or more people in the same priority category want to be appointed, they can apply jointly, which is common when adult children are involved and none has a clear reason to be appointed ahead of the others.</p>

      <p>Any application requires the applicant to demonstrate they are legally entitled to apply, that they are willing to act in accordance with their duties as administrator, and that they understand their obligations to the beneficiaries. The court does not rubber-stamp applications without reviewing these matters, though straightforward applications from clearly entitled applicants are typically processed without a hearing.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">What the administrator must do before listing the property</h2>
      <p>Once letters of administration are granted, the administrator has legal authority to deal with the estate's assets, but that authority comes with obligations. Before selling the property, the administrator must be registered on the title as administrator. This is a distinct step from obtaining the letters of administration, and it must be completed before any contract can be executed. The Queensland Titles Registry handles this, and the administrator's solicitor will typically lodge the necessary documents as part of their engagement.</p>

      <p>The administrator should also obtain a current market valuation of the property. This is not just good practice. It is part of the administrator's duty to the beneficiaries: they are required to administer the estate in a way that is fair to all beneficiaries, and that includes being able to demonstrate that the property was sold at or close to fair market value. A formal valuation from a registered valuer, taken close to the time of the sale, provides that documentation. It also protects the administrator personally if any beneficiary later questions the sale price.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">Timeline: how long does this process take?</h2>
      <p>Families often underestimate the time involved. From the date of death to the point where a property can be listed for sale, the process typically takes three to six months for a straightforward intestate estate, and sometimes longer. The application for letters of administration must be prepared (which requires obtaining a death certificate, identifying all assets and liabilities, drafting the application affidavit, and placing a public notice as required), lodged with the court, and then processed. Queensland court processing times vary. Once letters are granted, the registration of the administrator on title adds further time. Families should factor this into any plans that depend on a timely sale.</p>

      <p>Contested applications take considerably longer. If two family members disagree about who should be administrator, or if there is a dispute about whether the deceased had a valid will that was simply not found, the matter may require a court hearing. These disputes can extend the timeline by months or longer and add significantly to legal costs.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The administrator's duty to beneficiaries</h2>
      <p>The administrator does not own the estate's assets. They hold them on trust for the beneficiaries and must act accordingly. In a property sale context, this means marketing the property properly, not accepting an obviously undervalue offer, not selling to themselves or a connected party at a discount, and distributing the proceeds correctly after settlement. Administrators who breach these duties can be held personally liable. Families should understand that the administrator's role carries real legal responsibility, not just the practical task of managing the paperwork.</p>

      <p>Disputes among beneficiaries about whether to sell, when to sell, or what price to accept are unfortunately common, particularly where the property has been a long-held family home with emotional significance. Mediation is often more productive and far less expensive than litigation, and most experienced estate solicitors will suggest it as a first step when disagreements arise. If mediation fails, the Supreme Court can make orders about the sale, including appointing a statutory trustee to manage it.</p>

      <h2 style="font-family:var(--font-serif);font-size:1.5rem;font-weight:400;color:var(--color-text-primary);">The professional team you need</h2>
      <p>A Queensland solicitor experienced in deceased estates is the essential starting point. They will manage the letters of administration application, attend to title registration, advise on the administrator's duties, and handle conveyancing once the property is sold. An accountant familiar with deceased estates should also be engaged early, as there may be tax implications for the estate depending on how long the property was held and its use. The real estate agent's role is to run the campaign properly, present the property well, and achieve the best available market price, with the agent understanding that they are working to the administrator's instructions and that those instructions are bound by the administrator's legal obligations to the beneficiaries.</p>

